Owing to their strong solid-state blue emission, excellent thermal stability and suitable HOMOs/LUMOs, Py(5,9)BTPE and Py(5,9)BTriPE are adopted as emitting layers to fabricate the nondoped OLEDs. Multilayer devices are fabricated with a configuration of ITO/NPB (30 nm)/TCTA (10 nm)/Py(5,9)BTPE (device A) or Py(5,9)BTriPE (device B) (20 nm)/TPBi (40 nm)/LiF (1 nm)/Al (100 nm), in which NPB, TCTA, and TPBi function as a hole-transporting layer, an exciton-blocking layer and an electron-transporting layer, respectively [58]. The devices radiated a sky-blue and a pure-blue EL with a CIE coordinates of (0.19, 0.28) and (0.16, 0.17) for device A and device B, respectively, which are close to their corresponding PL of thin films, demonstrating that the exciton recombination occurs in the emitting layer and the EL originates from the radiative decays of singlet excitons (Fig. 9
                        ). The current density-voltage-luminance (J-V-L) characteristics and CE/PE/EQE versus current density curves of the two devices were shown in Fig. 10
                        . Two devices have a low turn-on voltage of 3.2 V, illustrating small injection barriers from the transporting layers to the emitting layers (Fig. 10a). Compared with that of Py(5,9)BTriPE-based device B, much better EL performances were achieved in Py(5,9)BTPE-based device A with enhanced CE, PE, and EQE values of 6.51 cd A−1, 6.24 lm W−1 and 3.35%, respectively, originating from the Py(5,9)BTPE is a typical AIE molecule with a higher PLQY of 57.7% in thin film. The EL data for the two devices are summarized in Table 2
                         [59,60]. Furthermore, a low efficiency roll-off (CE, PE and EQE) in the two devices was observed at high current desity of 200 mA cm−2 (Fig. 10b/10c), originating from their reasonable energy level matchments and device configurations (Fig. 10d). The EL emissions of the two devices are almost no change with the increasing of the current density from 0.1 to 10 mA cm−2, indicating their good color stability (Fig. 11
                        ). The EL performance of Py(5,9)BTPE-based device A can comparable with the OLEDs using pyrene-based AIEgens (Table 3
                        ).
